R=C3=A9sum=C3=A9 :
Cette th=C3=A8se s'inscrit dans le cadre du projet PERDIDO dont les =
objectifs sont l'extraction et la reconstruction d'itin=C3=A9raires =C3=A0=
 partir de documents textuels. Ces travaux ont =C3=A9t=C3=A9 r=C3=A9alis=C3=
=A9s en collaboration entre le laboratoire LIUPPA de l'universit=C3=A9 =
de Pau et des Pays de l'Adour (France), l'=C3=A9quipe IAAA de =
l'universit=C3=A9 de Saragosse (Espagne) et le laboratoire COGIT de =
l'IGN (France). Les objectifs de cette th=C3=A8se sont de concevoir un =
syst=C3=A8me automatique permettant d'extraire, dans des r=C3=A9cits de =
voyages ou des descriptions d=E2=80=99itin=C3=A9raires, des =
d=C3=A9placements, puis de les repr=C3=A9senter sur une carte.
Nous proposons une approche automatique pour la repr=C3=A9sentation d'un =
itin=C3=A9raire d=C3=A9crit en language naturel. Notre approche est =
compos=C3=A9e de deux t=C3=A2ches principales. La premi=C3=A8re t=C3=A2che=
 =C3=A0 pour r=C3=B4le d'identifier et d'extraire les informations qui =
d=C3=A9crivent l'itin=C3=A9raire dans le text, comme par exemple les =
entit=C3=A9s nomm=C3=A9es de lieux et les expressions de d=C3=A9placement =
ou de perception. La seconde t=C3=A2che =C3=A0 pour objectif la =
reconstruction de l'itin=C3=A9raire. Notre proposition combine =
l'utilisation d'information extraites gr=C3=A2ce au traitement =
automatique du language ainsi que des donn=C3=A9es extraites de =
ressources g=C3=A9ographiques externes (comme des gazetiers).
L'=C3=A9tape d'annotation d'informations spatiales est r=C3=A9alis=C3=A9e =
par une approche qui combine l'=C3=A9tiquetage morpho-syntaxique et des =
patrons lexico-syntaxiques (cascade de transducteurs) afin d'annoter des =
entit=C3=A9s nomm=C3=A9es spatiales et des expressions de d=C3=A9placement=
 ou de perception. Une premi=C3=A8re contribution au sein de la =
premi=C3=A8re t=C3=A2che est la d=C3=A9sambigu=C3=AFsation des =
toponymes, qui est un probl=C3=A8me encore mal r=C3=A9solu en NER et =
essentiel en recherche d'information g=C3=A9ographique. Nous proposons =
un algorithme non-supervis=C3=A9 de g=C3=A9o-r=C3=A9f=C3=A9rencement =
bas=C3=A9 sur une technique de clustering capable de proposer une =
solution pour d=C3=A9sambigu=C3=AFser les toponymes trouv=C3=A9s dans =
les ressources g=C3=A9ographiques externes, et dans le m=C3=AAme temps =
proposer une estimation de la localisation des toponymes non =
r=C3=A9f=C3=A9renc=C3=A9s.
Nous proposons un mod=C3=A8le de graphe g=C3=A9n=C3=A9rique pour la =
reconstruction automatique d'itin=C3=A9raire, o=C3=B9 chaque noeud =
repr=C3=A9sente un lieu et chaque segment repr=C3=A9sente un chemin =
reliant deux lieux. L'originalit=C3=A9 de notre mod=C3=A8le est qu'en =
plus de tenir compte des =C3=A9l=C3=A9ments habituels (chemins et points =
de passage), il permet de repr=C3=A9senter les autres =C3=A9l=C3=A9ments =
impliqu=C3=A9s dans la description d'un itin=C3=A9raire, comme par =
exemple les points de rep=C3=A8res visuels. Un calcul d'arbre de =
recouvrement minimal =C3=A0 partir d'un graphe pond=C3=A9r=C3=A9 est =
utilis=C3=A9 pour obtenir automatiquement un itin=C3=A9raire sous la =
forme d'un graphe. Chaque segment du graphe initial est pond=C3=A9r=C3=A9 =
en utilisant une m=C3=A9thode d'analyse multi-crit=C3=A8re combinant des =
crit=C3=A8res qualitatifs et des crit=C3=A8res quantitatifs. La valeur =
des crit=C3=A8res est d=C3=A9termin=C3=A9e =C3=A0 partir d'informations =
extraites du texte et d'informations provenant de ressources =
g=C3=A9ographique externes. Par exemple, nous combinons les informations =
issues du traitement automatique de la langue comme les relations =
spatiales d=C3=A9crivant une orientation (ex: se diriger vers le sud) =
avec les coordonn=C3=A9es g=C3=A9ographiques des lieux trouv=C3=A9s dans =
les ressources pour d=C3=A9terminer la valeur du crit=C3=A8re "relation =
spatiale".=20
De plus, =C3=A0 partir de la d=C3=A9finition du concept d'itin=C3=A9raire =
et des informations utilis=C3=A9es dans la langue pour d=C3=A9crire un =
itin=C3=A9raire, nous avons mod=C3=A9lis=C3=A9 un langage d'annotation =
d'information spatial adapt=C3=A9 =C3=A0 la description de =
d=C3=A9placements, s'appuyant sur les recommendations du consortium TEI =
(Text Encoding and Interchange).
Enfin, nous avons impl=C3=A9ment=C3=A9 et =C3=A9valu=C3=A9 les =
diff=C3=A9rentes =C3=A9tapes de notre approche sur un corpus multilingue =
de descriptions de randonn=C3=A9es (Fran=C3=A7ais, Espagnol et Italien).

Abstract :=20
This PhD thesis is part of the research project PERDIDO, which aims at =
extracting and retrieving displacements from textual documents. This =
work was conducted in collaboration with the LIUPPA laboratory of the =
university of Pau (France), the IAAA team of the university of Zaragoza =
(Spain) and the COGIT laboratory of IGN (France).
The objective of this PhD is to propose a method for establishing a =
processing chain to support the geoparsing and geocoding of text =
documents describing events strongly linked with space.
We propose an approach for the automatic geocoding of itineraries =
described in natural language.Our proposal is divided into two main =
tasks. The first task aims at identifying and extracting information =
describing the itinerary in texts such as spatial named entities and =
expressions of displacement or perception.The second task deal with the =
reconstruction of the itinerary. Our proposal combines local information =
extracted using natural language processing and physical features =
extracted from external geographical sources such as gazetteers or =
datasets providing digital elevation models.
The geoparsing part is a Natural Language Processing approach which =
combines the use of part of speech and syntactico-semantic combined =
patterns (cascade of transducers) for the annotation of spatial named =
entities and expressions of displacement or perception. The main =
contribution in the first task of our approach is the toponym =
disambiguation which represents an important issue in Geographical =
Information Retrieval (GIR).  We propose an unsupervised geocoding =
algorithm that takes profit of clustering techniques to provide a =
solution for disambiguating the toponyms found in gazetteers, and at the =
same time estimating the spatial footprint of those other fine-grain =
toponyms not found in gazetteers.
We propose a generic graph-based model for the automatic reconstruction =
of itineraries from texts, where each vertex represents a location and =
each edge represents a path between locations. %, combining information =
extracted from texts and information extracted from geographical =
databases. Our model is original in that in addition to taking into =
account the classic elements (paths and waypoints), it allows to =
represent the other elements describing an itinerary, such as features =
seen or mentioned as landmarks. To build automatically this graph-based =
representation of the itinerary, our approach computes an informed =
spanning tree on a weighted graph.
Each edge of the initial graph is weighted using a multi-criteria =
analysis approach combining qualitative and quantitative criteria. =
Criteria are based on information extracted from the text and =
information extracted from geographical sources. For instance, we =
compare information given in the text such as spatial relations =
describing orientation (e.g., going south) with the geographical =
coordinates of locations found in gazetteers.
Finally, according to the definition of an itinerary and the information =
used in natural language to describe itineraries, we propose a markup =
langugage for encoding spatial and motion information based on the Text =
Encoding and Interchange guidelines (TEI) which defines a standard for =
the representation of texts in digital form.
Additionally, the rationale of the proposed approach has been verified =
with a set of experiments on a corpus of multilingual hiking =
descriptions (French, Spanish and Italian).


